II. Algorithm: GPyOpt¶

  • Setup
In [5]:
# Parameter types: Continuous, Discrete, Choice
params = [sherpa.Discrete('alpha', [1, 180]),
          sherpa.Continuous('learning_rate', [0.01, 1]),
          sherpa.Discrete('max_depth', [10, 250])]

# Set algorithm of interest: GPyOpt
algo = bayesian_optimization.GPyOpt(max_num_trials=50)

study = sherpa.Study(parameters = params,
                     algorithm = algo,
                     lower_is_better = False)

In [7]:
def xgb_cv(alpha, learning_rate, max_depth, data, targets):
    le = LabelEncoder()
    target_ = le.fit_transform(targets)
    data_dmatrix = xgb.DMatrix(data = data, label = target_)

    params = {'objective':'binary:logistic',
              'max_depth': int(max_depth),
              'alpha': int(alpha),
              'learning_rate': learning_rate}

    xgb_cv_score = cv(dtrain = data_dmatrix, 
                      params = params, 
                      nfold = 4,
                      num_boost_round = 50, 
                      early_stopping_rounds = 10, 
                      metrics = "auc", 
                      as_pandas = True, 
                      seed = SEED)

    return xgb_cv_score["test-auc-mean"].mean()
In [8]:
for trial in study:    
    for i in range(epochs):
        # Train models in each epoch
        auc = xgb_cv(trial.parameters['alpha'], 
                     trial.parameters['learning_rate'], 
                     trial.parameters['max_depth'], 
                     X_train, 
                     y_train)
        
        study.add_observation(trial = trial, 
                              iteration = i,
                              objective = auc)
        if study.should_trial_stop(trial):
            
            break 
    study.finalize(trial = trial)

III. Algorithm: Asynchronous Successive Halving (ASHA)¶

  • Setup

We use $R$ = 9 and $\eta$ = 3 which mean to obtain one finished configuration we will train 9 configurations for 1 epochs, pick 3 configurations of those and train for 3 more epochs, then pick one out of those and train for another 9 epochs.

In [11]:
# Parameter types: Continuous, Discrete, Choice
params = [sherpa.Discrete('alpha', [1, 180]),
          sherpa.Continuous('learning_rate', [0.01, 1]),
          sherpa.Discrete('max_depth', [10, 250])]

# Set algorithm of interest: ASHA
algo = sherpa.algorithms.SuccessiveHalving(r=1, R=9, eta=3, s=0, max_finished_configs=1)

study = sherpa.Study(parameters = params,
                     algorithm = algo,
                     lower_is_better = False)
                     #disable_dashboard=True)

In [12]:
for trial in study:
    # Get number of training epochs
    initial_epoch = {1: 0, 3: 1, 9: 4}[trial.parameters['resource']]
    epochs = trial.parameters['resource'] + initial_epoch

    # Train model
    for i in range(initial_epoch, epochs):
        auc = xgb_cv(trial.parameters['alpha'], 
                     trial.parameters['learning_rate'], 
                     trial.parameters['max_depth'], 
                     X_train, 
                     y_train)
        
        study.add_observation(trial = trial, 
                              iteration = i,
                              objective = auc)
        if study.should_trial_stop(trial):
            break 
    study.finalize(trial = trial)
